<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>HEAT VENTILATION AIR CONDITIONING (HVAC), Orifice Tube System, Pre-March 2007 - 3200, 4100, 4200, 4300,
        4400, 7300, 7400, 7500, 7600, 7700, 8500, 8600 - AC PRESSURE TRANSDUCER CIRCUIT
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec id="hl1602567">
        <title>AC PRESSURE TRANSDUCER CIRCUIT</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="1">
            <title>CIRCUIT FUNCTIONS</title>
            <figure id="f1602573" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg16/G1602573.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 76. Pressure Transducer Function Diagram</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. AC COMPRESSOR</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. ELECTRICAL SYSTEM CONTROLLER (ESC)</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. ENGINE CONTROLLER</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. ENGINE COOLING FAN</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. AC PRESSURE TRANSDUCER</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>The refrigerant
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1602573">PRESSURE TRANSDUCER</hotlnk>
                allows the ESC to monitor the refrigerant pressure in the A/C system. This information is used by the
                ESC software program (the RCD system) to help control the operation of the A/C system, and to help
                diagnose faults during abnormal system operation. For a complete description of the RCD system, refer to
                <hotlnk document="s16025_HL1602568.xml" xrefid="hl1602568">SECTION 8.1</hotlnk>
                <xref refid="hl1602568"/>.
            </para>
            <para>The ESC will generate diagnostic trouble codes if the readings received from the pressure transducer
                are either out of range high or out of range low.
            </para>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
